Here's the thing: As the Ink Spots sang about loneliness and missing someone and sadness, the subject (man/fish) seemed physically smaller on the card.  And I thought that was a really cool effect.
The tone matches the card, but TBH the whimsy of this song could be applied to like, at least 50% of all Dixit cards.

I didn't like the melody.  But some of the lyrics were moving ("Embers in the dark / Can look just like shooting stars / To a bitter, broken heart). And I really liked the visual connections to the Dixit card - the background looks like a sky on fire, the bushes look like flames, and the man who broke her heart left without her.

That's the dude from "Mary Poppins" y'all!  And the same composers too.  I was not a huge fan of the song (too cheesy?), but I will say, they made some things rhyme very nicely (when was the last time you heard a song successfully incorporate "promenade" rhymes, or include words like "bobbing" and "briny" in a kids' song?).  The fish isn't bobbing along in the beautiful briny sea though - he's in the forest.

For me personally this song's vibe didn't mesh well with the card.  The card is describing excitement over a group going to some sort of utopian wonderland, and I don't see that sort of excitement on this kid's face.  Wherever he's going, he's not all that excited to be going there.

Nature setting, check.  Someone who's not all that happy, check.  Ocean imagery, check.  I liked the idea of the Dixit card matching the theme of moments passing by - this boy is with this fish in this place for just a moment, and then he'll be gone, like the moments in this song.
